text='''Presenter: Georgia S'''    %0a!![[http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3437663/|Skin infection generates non-migratory memory CD8+ TRM cells providing global skin immunity]]%0a%0a%25whoo hoo PMC link FTW%25%0a%0a!!!Comments from DWC via email%0a%0a*The main point I come away with is: OT-I (CD8+) cells provide viral clearance of VACV-Ova in the skin and this is non-migratory, similarly mice previously infected with VACV have may have a major non-migratory factor that supresses viral replication. But I'm not convinced that it's resident memory. They are unable to put the cells back in and test that direct hypothesis. Therefore, it could be an unknown soluble factor or a S1P independent migratory cell that drives the phenotype.%0a*I'm bothered by the over selling of the impact on skin immunity. Given that we know cytotoxic CD8+ cells mediate viral clearance I doubt (but am open to the reality) that these cells will be important in other skin pathogen models.%0a*All in all it's a really cool phenotype but I'm not sure the controls indicate definitively the role of non-migratory cells. There is a strong suggestion that there is a non-migratory component. One point that suggests it might be a migratory component is the treatment after separation opening up the possibility that there is an induced migration upon infection that clears the virus (S1P independent I admittedly know very little about the types and factors in immune cell migration)
